{"title":"PointDistiller: Structured Knowledge Distillation Towards Efficient and Compact 3D Detection","domain":"CV","seeds":[{"problem":"Feature- or prediction-level knowledge distillation methods designed for images transfer poorly to point-cloud 3D detectors because point clouds are sparse, irregular, and lack explicit topology. Students need to inherit a teacher’s understanding of local geometric structure rather than only global backbone features.","method":"Introduce local distillation that explicitly distills local geometric structure. For the top-N sampled voxels/points, build KNN neighborhoods and encode them with dynamic graph convolution (DGCNN-style) after fusing the neighborhood with the center feature, producing graph features for teacher and student. Train with a feature-matching loss on these graph features; the graph conv adapters are learned jointly with the student and discarded at inference, making the approach lightweight and architecture-agnostic. (Supported by: Section 1 ‘Local Distillation’; Sec. 3.2 ‘Extracting Local Geometric Information’ incl. KNN graphs and dynamic graph conv; note on discarding layers at inference.)"},{"problem":"In point clouds, most voxels contain very few (often single, noisy) points, and many points are uninformative. Uniformly distilling all locations wastes student capacity and reduces KD effectiveness on 3D detection.","method":"Use importance-aware distillation to focus on informative regions. Define per-voxel importance as the number of points inside the voxel and per-point importance as the teacher feature’s channel-wise maximum (a saliency score). Sample the top-N voxels/points by these scores for distillation, then reweight the KD loss with a softmax-temperature weighting derived from importance (for voxels) or from the teacher’s graph features/saliency (for points), so higher-importance neighborhoods contribute more to the loss. This sampling-and-reweighting works for both voxel- and point-based detectors and plugs directly into standard training. (Supported by: Sec. 3.2 ‘Sampling TopN To-be-distilled Voxels (Points)’; Sec. 3.2 ‘Reweighting Knowledge Distillation Loss’ with φ=softmax(·/τ); Fig. 2 and description on sparsity.)"}]}
